# Experimental Results and Performance Analysis

This document provides an empirical analysis of the Multi-Mode Autonomous Smart Robot Car, detailing its performance across manual and autonomous operational modes.

## 1. Movement and Kinematic Control
The platform demonstrated high-precision movement and responsiveness. The integration of the L298N motor driver allowed for stable execution of directional commands.
* **Manual Mode Performance:** Using the HC-05 Bluetooth interface, the system achieved a low-latency connection with the smartphone application. 
* **Observation:** Command execution was instantaneous, validating the efficiency of the wireless control logic and the real-time processing capability of the Arduino Uno.

## 2. Obstacle Avoidance Reliability
The ultrasonic sensing suite was tested to validate the collision prevention mechanism.
* **Detection Accuracy:** The HC-SR04 sensor effectively mapped obstacles within the predefined **20 cm threshold**.
* **Evasive Action Logic:** Upon detection, the "Stop-Reverse-Pivot" sequence was triggered with 100% reliability. This confirmed that the interrupt-style logic in the firmware is capable of neutralizing vehicle inertia to prevent physical impact.



## 3. Path-Tracking (Line Following) Accuracy
The infrared (IR) sensor array was evaluated on high-contrast surfaces to test the robustness of the tracking algorithm.
* **Surface Analysis:** The sensors successfully identified the contrast between black and white surfaces, maintaining the robot's alignment on a predefined track.
* **Corrective Maneuvers:** The system demonstrated efficient deviation correction. When the robot drifted, the differential steering logic immediately realigned the chassis, proving the robustness of the binary state-machine implemented in the code.

